   "source": [
    "### 2.7 Distance aux grands parcs (feature engineering géospatial)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "1f1dac81",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "On calcule la distance (en km) entre chaque annonce et deux points de référence — Central Park et Prospect Park — via la formule de Haversine, pour voir si la proximité d'un grand parc influence le prix."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "58d0459b",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def distance_haversine(lat1, lon1, lat2, lon2):\n",
    "    \"\"\"Distance approximative en km entre deux points GPS.\"\"\"\n",
    "    return np.arccos(\n",
    "        np.sin(np.radians(lat1)) * np.sin(np.radians(lat2))\n",
    "        + np.cos(np.radians(lat1)) * np.cos(np.radians(lat2)) * np.cos(np.radians(lon1 - lon2))\n",
    "    ) * 6371\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "lat_central_park, lon_central_park = 40.785091, -73.968285\n",
    "lat_prospect_park, lon_prospect_park = 40.665535, -73.969749\n",
    "\n",
    "df[\"Distance Central Park\"] = distance_haversine(\n",
    "    lat_central_park, lon_central_park, df[\"Latitude\"], df[\"Longitude\"]\n",
    ").round(4)\n",
    "df[\"Distance Prospect Park\"] = distance_haversine(\n",
    "    lat_prospect_park, lon_prospect_park, df[\"Latitude\"], df[\"Longitude\"]\n",
    ").round(4)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "9ea37fe4",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "manhattan_proche_cp = df[(df[\"Arrondissement\"] == \"Manhattan\") & (df[\"Prix\"] < 300)]\n",
    "\n",
    "fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 10))\n",
    "sns.scatterplot(x=\"Distance Central Park\", y=\"Prix\", data=manhattan_proche_cp, ax=ax)\n",
    "ax.set_title(\"Prix des annonces à Manhattan selon la distance à Central Park\");"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "b277f3d8",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 3. Modélisation prédictive du prix\n",
    "\n",
    "Objectif : prédire le `Prix` d'une annonce à partir de son type de logement, son arrondissement, ses contraintes de réservation et sa popularité — sans utiliser d'information géographique fine (quartier, latitude/longitude) ni de texte, pour garder un modèle simple et généralisable."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "adbdb257",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "df[\"Mois actif\"] = df[\"Nombre avis\"] / df[\"Avis par mois\"]\n",
    "\n",
    "variables_explicatives = [\"Type\", \"Arrondissement\", \"Minimum nuits\", \"Nombre avis\", \"Jours disponibles annuel\", \"Mois actif\"]\n",
    "X = df[variables_explicatives]\n",
    "y = df[\"Prix\"]\n",
    "\n",
    "variables_num = list(X.select_dtypes(exclude=[\"object\"]))\n",
    "variables_cat = list(X.select_dtypes(include=[\"object\"]))\n",
    "\n",
    "X_train, X_val, y_train, y_val = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.25, random_state=1)\n",
    "print(f\"Entraînement : {X_train.shape}, Validation : {X_val.shape}\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "d8c87a18",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### 3.1 Imputation, encodage et standardisation"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "ecd301d4",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "index_train, index_val = X_train.index, X_val.index\n",
    "\n",
    "# Imputation des variables numériques (médiane) et catégorielles (mode), calibrée sur l'entraînement uniquement\n",
    "imp_num = SimpleImputer(strategy=\"median\").fit(X_train[variables_num])\n",
    "X_train_num = pd.DataFrame(imp_num.transform(X_train[variables_num]), columns=variables_num, index=index_train)\n",
    "X_val_num = pd.DataFrame(imp_num.transform(X_val[variables_num]), columns=variables_num, index=index_val)\n",
    "\n",
    "imp_cat = SimpleImputer(strategy=\"most_frequent\").fit(X_train[variables_cat])\n",
    "X_train_cat = pd.DataFrame(imp_cat.transform(X_train[variables_cat]), columns=variables_cat, index=index_train)\n",
    "X_val_cat = pd.DataFrame(imp_cat.transform(X_val[variables_cat]), columns=variables_cat, index=index_val)\n",
    "\n",
    "X_train = pd.concat([X_train_num, X_train_cat], axis=1)\n",
    "X_val = pd.concat([X_val_num, X_val_cat], axis=1)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "42cce5a5",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Encodage one-hot des variables catégorielles\n",
    "encodeur = ColumnTransformer(\n",
    "    transformers=[(\"encoder\", OneHotEncoder(drop=\"first\"), variables_cat)],\n",
    "    remainder=\"passthrough\",\n",
    ")\n",
    "X_train = pd.DataFrame(encodeur.fit_transform(X_train), columns=encodeur.get_feature_names_out(), index=index_train)\n",
    "X_val = pd.DataFrame(encodeur.transform(X_val), columns=encodeur.get_feature_names_out(), index=index_val)\n",
    "\n",
    "colonnes_encodees = X_train.columns\n",
    "\n",
    "# Standardisation robuste (moins sensible aux valeurs extrêmes que StandardScaler)\n",
    "standardiseur = RobustScaler().fit(X_train)\n",
    "X_train = pd.DataFrame(standardiseur.transform(X_train), columns=colonnes_encodees, index=index_train)\n",
    "X_val = pd.DataFrame(standardiseur.transform(X_val), columns=colonnes_encodees, index=index_val)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "bda62877",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### 3.2 Analyse des corrélations"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "fe98ca88",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "train = pd.concat([X_train, y_train], axis=1)\n",
    "corr_matrix = train.corr().abs()\n",
    "np.fill_diagonal(corr_matrix.values, 0)\n",
    "\n",
    "fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 12))\n",
    "sns.heatmap(corr_matrix, ax=ax)\n",
    "ax.set_title(\"Matrice de corrélation des variables\");"
